## Methods

### 1. Gaussian Goodness-of-Fit Testing

A statistical goodness-of-fit test was applied to determine whether the first measurement feature could be considered Gaussian.

### 2. Bayes Classification Error

Bayes classification error was calculated using:

- The first measurement feature only
- The second measurement feature only
- All available measurement features

This helped compare how much classification information was contained in different feature sets.

### 3. Data Normalization

When using all available measurement features, normalization was applied to ensure that features were compared on a consistent scale.

### 4. Neural Network Classification

A neural network classifier was trained using the available measurement features. The dataset was partitioned into training and testing sets to evaluate classification error.

### 5. Correlation Analysis

Pairwise statistical correlation coefficients were computed between measurement features to assess linear relationships and discuss whether the features could be considered statistically independent.

### 6. Correlation vs. Mutual Information

The project compared correlation and mutual information:

- Correlation measures linear relationships between variables
- Mutual information can capture more general statistical dependence, including nonlinear relationships

This distinction is important because two features can be uncorrelated but still share mutual information.

